Each P1 process step is a numbered stage in the make-map pipeline. A step owns six files: the generator or adjustor ("p1_*_*.cpp" / ".h"), a test driver ("p1_*_tester.cpp") and its compile script ("p1_*_comp"), and a view helper ("p1_*_view.cpp" / ".h") that converts game-format overlays into easily viewable images (PPM). The test driver must not embed ad-hoc RGB blending; it calls the view helper and the stage's own "save_output" where that already exists; "save_output" should only exist for a small set of overlays that contain runtime data, as opposed to intermediate data. The view helper is the single place for terrain/climate/river tint rules specific to that step's outputs. Parameters for each generator / adjustor will either be placed as a define in the cpp-file, if intended to be tweaked at design-time and used as a constant, or in a struct that aggregates all parameters eventually meant to be exposed. Exposed tunables are listed once in "P1_MapConfig" ("p1_map_config.h", included from "p1_tester_util.h"); "p1_map_config_def()" is the only place default values are set. Each step also owns a local "P1_*Prm" subset struct in its own header; a step-local inline copies the relevant fields from "P1_MapConfig" into that subset. Per-step "P1_*Prm" structs must stay in the step source header, not in shared util or make-map headers. Processing speed is a high priority, so all test drivers should time the generator / adjustor. Use "P1_RPrint": "rprint_state_*" for normal metrics, "rprint_result_*" only for failed asserts, "rprint_info" for timing and paths. 

Each test driver uses "P1_TesterHarness": "begin()" checks out the step from "g_p1_tester_tbl", clears the seed output folder, parses CLI via "P1_TesterCli", and loads "P1_MapConfig" from "p1_map_config_def()"; "run_input()" runs the shared prereq chain in memory only; when "full" is set, the harness also calls "p1_tester_save_early_views()" (in "p1_tester_early_views.h" / ".cpp") to write canonical PPMs for prereq steps through "m_in_step" using each step's view helper; the driver runs the stage under test; "finish()" frees chain memory and checks the whiteboard. Shared CLI parsing lives in "P1_TesterCli" ("p1_tester_cli.h" / ".cpp"): positional args are "[seed] [w] [h] [lap×5 floats]" (seed from "seed.txt" when omitted); flags are "full" (save prereq view outputs via the harness) and "--rain-wt=N" (climate steps). Harness exposes "cfg()", "full()", "lap()", "rain_wt()", and "rain_wt_set()"; legacy "p1_resolve_*" helpers in "p1_tester_util.h" delegate to the same parser. Default runs stay fast by writing only the step-under-test canonical output; disk I/O for prereq steps is avoided unless "full" is passed. Canonical outputs are at most two per step ("m_out_pri", "m_out_sec" in the table), via "path_pri()" / "path_sec()". Extra debug images use "path_extra(suffix)" and are saved only when that driver is run. Per-step drivers still save their own primary (and secondary) output; "full" adds prereq PPMs only, not step-specific extras.

Each generator and adjustor avoids heap allocation ("new" / "delete") for temporary work buffers. Scratch storage uses whiteboard classes ("WbSheet", "WB_QueXY", paired u16 sheets for u32 fields) with checkout released before return; this keeps allocation overhead low and supports fast per-tile passes. Persistent step results live in owned buffers on the result struct or in caller-provided overlays, not in leaked whiteboard slots. The harness's "finish()" whiteboard check is the guard against regressions.

Prereq data always comes from one pipeline pass—"P1_MakeMap" through "m_in_step", or the chain15 helpers for steps 18–22—not from a separate rebuild on different terrain or rivers. New steps are registered in "g_p1_tester_tbl" with "m_in_kind", "m_in_step", and canonical filenames. Compile scripts for chain-backed testers should source "p1_build_core_map_objs.sh" or "p1_build_river_chain_objs.sh" rather than duplicating link lines. Refactor existing steps toward this layout over time; full compliance is the target, not a requirement for every file today.
